## Finding: Canary Deployment Verification Has No Automated Promotion/Abort Gate

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: The deployment_patterns skill mentions canary deployments conceptually (traffic splitting percentages, "route 5% of traffic"), and the mlops skill goes further with Kubernetes/Istio canary configs. However, neither skill nor any other in Phase 5 provides: (1) a signal-based automatic promotion/abort mechanism — i.e. "if error rate exceeds X% during canary window, abort automatically"; (2) a standardized canary verification step that must pass before full rollout; (3) integration between deployment tooling and observability to make rollout decisions. The ci_cd_pipeline skill's deploy stages go directly from "build" to "deploy to production" with no canary gate. The rollback section only covers manual revert-commit or CLI commands — it is entirely reactive, not proactive.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `canary_verification` in Phase 5 (or major expansion of deployment_patterns). Triggers: "canary deployment", "progressive rollout", "automated rollout verification". Scope: Implements automated canary promotion gates using error rate, latency p99, and business metric thresholds. Covers: GitHub Actions workflow step that polls metrics after canary deploy and aborts/promotes based on configurable thresholds; integrates with Datadog/Prometheus/Grafana; provides rollback-on-signal automation. Should cover both app-level and ML model canary verification.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5.5 (Alpha) health_checks skill detects problems post-deploy but has no upstream feedback loop into Phase 5's deployment pipeline. Phase 4 (Secure) performance_testing validates baselines but no mechanism carries those baselines forward as canary abort criteria.

