## Finding: Reverse-Think: A Perfect Phase 5 Completion MUST Have Deployment Verification — But No Skill Ensures It

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Working backward from "Phase 5 completed perfectly": the team has a production deployment running, verified working. For this to be true, SOMEONE must have confirmed: (1) the deployed container/service is serving live traffic correctly; (2) the health endpoint returns 200; (3) the critical user flows work (login, core feature, payment if applicable); (4) error rate is not elevated; (5) performance is within baseline. Now checking: what Phase 5 skill ensures this happened? The ci_cd_pipeline deploys to Railway and exits. The deployment_patterns checklist has items to check but no automation. No skill provides a "deployment verification" automated step that answers "did this deployment succeed from a user perspective?" The mlops skill uniquely has `monitor_canary.py --rollback-on-error` but this is only for ML models. The gap is a deployment verification skill that runs after every production deploy.
### Proposed Resolution: Skill: `deployment_verification`. Triggers: "verify deployment", "post-deploy check", "deployment health check". Scope: A standardized post-deployment verification workflow that: (1) waits for rolling deploy to complete; (2) hits critical API endpoints and asserts expected responses; (3) checks that error rate hasn't spiked (using platform APIs); (4) confirms new version hash is running (version endpoint); (5) notifies team on success or triggers automatic rollback on failure. This is different from Phase 5.5 health_checks (which is operational, not deployment-gated).
### Cross-Phase Impact: This is the last gate before Phase 5.5 takes over. Without it, Phase 5.5 may receive a broken deployment and spend time diagnosing what should have been caught at deploy time.

================================================================

## Finding: Reverse-Think: A Perfect Phase 5 MUST Have All Secrets in Prod — But No Skill Verifies the Secrets Inventory

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Working backward from a successful Phase 5: production has all required secrets configured (DATABASE_URL, JWT_SECRET, API keys, etc.). For this to be true, there must be a mechanism to know WHICH secrets are required and verify they are present. Current state: the ci_cd_pipeline lists some secrets in a table (RAILWAY_TOKEN, VERCEL_TOKEN, etc.) as documentation. The env_validation skill (Phase 5.5) validates at runtime. But: (1) there is no Phase 5 pre-deploy step that checks "are all required secrets configured in the target environment before deploying?"; (2) if a new secret is added to the codebase (e.g. a new AI provider key), there is no mechanism to catch that it's missing from production before the deploy; (3) the infrastructure_as_code skill mentions secrets management best practices but provides no inventory or verification automation. A deploy to production failing because of a missing secret is embarrassing and avoidable.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to ci_cd_pipeline a "pre-deploy secrets validation" step: enumerate required env var names from a committed `.env.example` or schema file; call the platform's secrets API (Railway environment API, GitHub Environment secrets API) to verify each one exists; fail the deploy if any are missing. This is distinct from validating values (which requires runtime) — just checking presence.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5.5 env_validation catches this at runtime (app startup). Phase 5 should catch it pre-deploy. The gap means the first notification of a missing secret is a production startup failure, not a CI check.

================================================================

## Finding: Reverse-Think: A Perfect Phase 5 OSS Release MUST Be Tamper-Proof — Current OSS Publishing is Not

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Working backward from a secure OSS release: consumers of the npm/PyPI package can verify it came from the canonical source and was not tampered with. The oss_publishing skill covers semantic-release, npm publish, and PyPI publishing. But: (1) npm publish does not enable provenance by default — consumers cannot verify the package was built from the specific GitHub commit; (2) there is no mention of `npm publish --provenance` (requires OIDC token, supported since npm 9.5+); (3) no mention of PyPI's Trusted Publishers mechanism; (4) no mention of GPG signing for Git tags (signed releases); (5) no discussion of the `package-lock.json` integrity verification in the publishing pipeline. Supply chain attacks on npm packages (XZ Utils style) are a real threat that this skill ignores.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Package Provenance" section to oss_publishing: (1) enable `--provenance` in npm publish workflow using OIDC token; (2) configure PyPI Trusted Publishers instead of API tokens; (3) sign Git release tags with GPG; (4) generate and publish SBOM alongside each release; (5) verify package contents with `npm pack --dry-run` before publish in CI.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) security_audit covers code security but not supply chain security for published packages. Phase 7 (Maintenance) has no mechanism to audit published package integrity after the fact.

