## Finding: Failure Mode — Multi-Service Deploy Partial Failure Has No Recovery Skill

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: The ci_cd_pipeline skill has separate workflows for backend (deploy-backend.yml) and frontend (deploy-frontend.yml). In a mono-repo with multiple deployment targets, they can succeed independently. Failure mode: backend deploys successfully (migrated DB, new code running), but frontend deploy fails. Now production has: new backend API (potentially breaking changes in responses) + old frontend code. Or: backend deploy fails AFTER migration runs. This partial deployment state is not addressed by any Phase 5 skill. There is no: (1) "atomic multi-service deployment" concept; (2) "rollback all on partial failure" mechanism; (3) detection that backend and frontend are out of sync; (4) API versioning strategy to survive the window of mismatch. The deploy workflows are fire-and-forget with no cross-workflow coordination.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to ci_cd_pipeline: (1) a deployment coordinator workflow that sequences backend and frontend deploys and rolls back both on failure of either; (2) API version header (`X-API-Version`) pattern that frontend sends, allowing backend to serve old and new API simultaneously during the rollout window; (3) feature flag pattern to disable new features during partial deployment state. Also add a "Multi-Service Deploy Coordination" section to deployment_patterns.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5.5 health_checks would detect this failure after the fact, but there's no automated recovery. Phase 4's integration tests may not catch frontend/backend API mismatches if they test each in isolation.

