## Finding: DORA Metrics — Phase 5 Has No Deployment Frequency or Lead Time Instrumentation

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: DORA (DevOps Research and Assessment) defines four key metrics: Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, and Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR). Elite performers deploy multiple times per day with lead times under one hour. Phase 5 skills implement CI/CD pipelines but measure nothing: (1) no deployment frequency tracking — no skill captures "how many deployments per week" as a metric; (2) no lead time measurement — no step records time from first commit to production deploy; (3) no change failure rate tracking — no step records whether a deployment resulted in a rollback or incident; (4) no MTTR measurement — no skill connects incidents to their resolution. Without measuring these, teams cannot improve them and cannot benchmark against industry standards. DORA metrics are now industry standard (referenced in Google's SRE book, State of DevOps Report) and have no representation in Phase 5.
### Proposed Resolution: Add "Deployment Metrics" section to ci_cd_pipeline. Implement: (1) deployment event logging to a database or metrics service (LinearB, Sleuth, or custom) at the end of each deploy workflow; (2) deployment duration tracking (commit SHA → production timestamp); (3) rollback event logging (which commits, how long it took); (4) weekly DORA metrics report as a GitHub Actions scheduled workflow. Triggers: "deployment metrics", "DORA metrics", "deployment frequency".
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 (Maintenance) performance improvement is impossible without baseline DORA metrics from Phase 5. Phase 5.5 (Alpha) quality metrics have no deployment context.

