## Finding: SOC 2 / ISO 27001 — Change Management Requirements Not Met by Phase 5

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: SOC 2 Type II and ISO 27001 both require formal change management: (1) all production changes must be authorized before implementation; (2) changes must be tested before applying to production; (3) a change log must exist with who approved, what changed, when, and the result; (4) emergency changes must follow an expedited but still controlled process. Phase 5 skills: ci_cd_pipeline uses GitHub Environments with required reviewers for production — this partially addresses (1) for code. But: there is no skill covering: (a) database migration change approval records; (b) infrastructure change records (Terraform apply produces output but it's not stored as a change record); (c) formal rollback authorization records; (d) the concept of a "Change Advisory Board" (CAB) meeting or equivalent approval workflow for high-risk changes; (e) audit log retention requirements for change records. For SaaS companies pursuing SOC 2, this is a compliance gap.
### Proposed Resolution: Add "Change Management Records" section to ci_cd_pipeline or create a new `change_management` skill. Covers: (1) structured change record format stored as GitHub Issues or in a dedicated system; (2) automated change record creation from deployment events; (3) linking deployments to change records; (4) emergency change procedure with post-incident review requirement; (5) change record retention (typically 1 year for SOC 2). Rated HIGH because SOC 2 is a standard requirement for B2B SaaS.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) security_audit does not cover change management from an audit perspective. Phase 6 (Handoff) documentation has no change log artifact from Phase 5.

================================================================

## Finding: NIST SSDF (Secure Software Development Framework) — Phase 5 Missing Provenance and Integrity Requirements

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: NIST SP 800-218 (SSDF) and Executive Order 14028 (US) require software producers to: (1) maintain provenance of all software components; (2) provide a software bill of materials (SBOM) to customers; (3) use signed artifacts in the release pipeline; (4) implement vulnerability disclosure processes. For Phase 5: (1) SBOM generation is absent from all skills except indirectly mentioned in the gap identified in Loop 1; (2) artifact signing (cosign, Sigstore) is absent; (3) there is no vulnerability disclosure process in Phase 5 — the oss_publishing skill has SECURITY.md templates for OSS, but no equivalent for proprietary SaaS products; (4) the legal_compliance skill covers GDPR/CCPA but not cybersecurity regulatory requirements (NIST, CMMC for US government contractors). This is increasingly relevant as regulations like EU Cyber Resilience Act take effect.
### Proposed Resolution: Add "Regulatory Compliance - Software Security" section to Phase 5 (either as a section in legal_compliance or a new skill). Cover: (1) SBOM generation with syft or cdxgen in CI pipeline; (2) SBOM distribution to enterprise customers; (3) vulnerability disclosure policy template (CVD); (4) NIST SSDF mapping checklist. Add artifact signing to infrastructure_as_code and oss_publishing.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 security_audit covers code-level vulnerabilities but not supply-chain and provenance requirements. Phase 6 (Handoff) has no mechanism to deliver SBOMs to customers.

