## Finding: SRE Practices — Error Budget and SLO/SLI Concepts Absent from Phase 5

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Google SRE (Site Reliability Engineering) practices, now widely adopted across the industry, define: SLIs (Service Level Indicators — what you measure), SLOs (Service Level Objectives — target values for SLIs), and Error Budgets (how much unreliability you can "spend" before pausing feature releases). Phase 5 skills: deployment_patterns mentions "monitoring alerts" and "uptime monitoring" but: (1) no skill defines how to set SLOs for a Phase 5 deployment; (2) no skill connects the error budget concept to deployment velocity (when error budget is exhausted, deployments should slow or stop); (3) no skill defines what SLIs to track (request latency p50/p95/p99, error rate, availability, saturation); (4) the ci_cd_pipeline has no "error budget gate" — if error budget is consumed, new feature deploys should be blocked. This is an industry-standard practice missing from the framework.
### Proposed Resolution: Add "SLO and Error Budget" section to deployment_patterns. Define: (1) standard SLIs for web applications; (2) SLO configuration in monitoring tools (Datadog SLOs, Prometheus recording rules); (3) error budget calculation; (4) "error budget policy" — what happens when budget is exhausted (freeze deployments, write post-mortems); (5) integrate error budget check into the deployment gate (if budget < X%, require manual approval). Triggers: "SLO", "error budget", "service level objectives".
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5.5 health_checks monitors operational health but has no SLO/error budget concept. Phase 7 (Maintenance) improvement cycles should be driven by SLO violations but there's no connection.

